$section Problems Using Mozilla 1.3 To Display OMhelp Output$$
$mindex bugzilla mozilla browser display error$$

$children/
	latex\NegativeSpace.omh/$$

$head Description$$
The 
$href%http://www.mozilla.org/Mozilla/%Mozilla%$$ 
browser can display both XHTML and MathML commands.
Below is a list of cases where version 1.3 of Mozilla
appears to have problems displaying MathML commands.
If you have any feed back,
please send e-mail to:
$href%mailto:bradbell@seanet.com%bradbell@seanet.com%$$.

$head XHTML$$

$subhead Javascript$$
The following problem occurs when
using Javascript with XHTML files 
You can select this link to $execute MozillaJavascriptXml.xml$$
which contains the following XML commands:
$pre
$$
$nospell
$codep
<?xml version='1.0'?>
<?xml-stylesheet type='text/xsl' href='pmathml.xsl'?>
<html xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml'>
	<head></head>
	<body>
		The word "Test" should (but does not) 
		appear in the text area below:
		<br/>
		<form name="search">
			<textarea name="list" rows="1" cols="20" ></textarea>
		</form>
		<script type='text/javascript'>
			document.search.list.value    = "Test";
		</script>
	</body>
</html>
$$
$$
$pre
$$
As noted above, the word $code Test$$ should appear 
in the text area, but it does not.

$subhead Background Color$$
The following problem occurs when
setting the background color  with XML files 
You can select the link to $execute MozillaBackgroundXml.xml$$
which contains the following XML commands:
$pre
$$
$nospell
$codep
<?xml version='1.0'?>
<?xml-stylesheet type='text/xsl' href='pmathml.xsl'?>
<html xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml'>
	<head></head>
	<body style ='background-color : rgb(210, 210, 210)'>
		The background color around this text is a light shade of gray.
		The problem is that when displayed by Mozilla,
		it is surrounded by a white border.
	</body>
</html>
$$
$$
On the other hand, HTML files 
are displayed properly as can be seen by selecting the link
$execute MozillaBackgroundXml.htm$$
which contains the following HTML commands:
$pre
$$
$nospell
$codep
<html>
	<head></head>
	<body style ='background-color : rgb(210, 210, 210)'>
		The background color around this text is a light shade of gray.
		In this case,  Mozilla does not surrounded it by a white border.
	</body>
</html>
$$
$$

$head MathML$$

$subhead Negative Space$$
$mindex negative space$$
A positive space display is demonstrated by 
the following input
$codep
	<mi>=</mi><mspace width="1em"/><mi>/</mi>
$$
which generates the output
$latex \[ \mathml{
	<mi>=</mi><mspace width="1em"/><mi>/</mi>
} \] $$
The negative spaces do not display as expected 
as demonstrated by the following input
$codep
	<mi>=</mi><mspace width="-1em"/><mi>/</mi>
$$
which generates the output
$latex \[ \mathml{
	<mi>=</mi><mspace width="-1em"/><mi>/</mi>
} \] $$
A formal bug report for this is given in the section
$center
$tref NegativeSpace$$
$$

$subhead Operator Sizes$$
$mindex operator size$$
The specification of the minimum size attribute
does not seem to work for some operators
(the $code &cap;$$ character has unicode hex value $code 02229$$).
For example
$codep
	<mo minsize="2em">(</mo> 
	<mo minsize="2em">&#x02229;</mo> 
	<mo minsize="2em">)</mo> 
$$
generates the output
$latex \[ \mathml{ 
	<mo minsize="2em">(</mo> 
	<mo minsize="2em">&#x02229;</mo> 
	<mo minsize="2em">)</mo> 
} \]$$

